			<title>Child Custody Advice</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78135-Child-Custody-Advice&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Thu, 17 Sep 2015 18:55:05 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[I need advice from the board, something I don't think I've ever done here, but I am beginning to lose hope.  To be clear, this case involves a friend, not me (yes really).  I apologize for this being long, but it's a long story. 
 
A friend has been going through a divorce for over a year now.  She...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>I need advice from the board, something I don't think I've ever done here, but I am beginning to lose hope.  To be clear, this case involves a friend, not me (yes really).  I apologize for this being long, but it's a long story.<br />
<br />
A friend has been going through a divorce for over a year now.  She doesn't have many assets, so it's mostly held up because of child custody and the fact the father still seems to think they can get back together.  His parents also have money, which has allowed him to get a better lawyer and really drag out the case.<br />
<br />
Normally I would not interject myself into such matters, except he's a heroin addict and the now 3 year old girl caught in the middle is a very nice innocent child and friend of my 2 year old daughter.<br />
<br />
But here is where things have gotten crazy and causes so much despair.  Despite the father having drug convictions in the last 2 years and and not finishing court appointed rehabilitation,  the court still sides with him every single time they go to court.<br />
<br />
My friend obviously wants sole custody, however she's been willing to split custody if he agreed to drug tests (which he refuses for obvious reasons).  I believe child custody specifically is still in mediation, a judge may not have ruled on some of that.<br />
<br />
But last week things turned south.  About a month ago he showed up to a kid's birthday party either drunk or high.  My friend was obviously not there, but the daughter was (it was a birthday party for another child at daycare).  The other parents at this party were so concerned from his behavior that many of them called child protective services (great!).<br />
<br />
CPS first issued a protection order, saying my friend should not allow visitation again until heard by a judge (that makes sense!).  But then, a couple of days later they call her up and tell her &quot;well, our order of protection really has no authority, you still have to allow access.  But if anything happens it's still your fault&quot;.  And a few days after that they said the order of protection was rescinded.  Keep in mind this whole time the father was never once drug tested (although heroin can be tough since it can be out of your system in as little as 3 days).<br />
<br />
However, because she refused to allow visitation because of this obvious problem, his lawyer filed contempt charges on her.  Which brings us back to last week where she was found guilty of contempt and ordered to pay his lawyer $1000 for refusing visitation 2 times.  If CPS getting calls from 3rd party parents does not warrant clear danger wtf does?<br />
<br />
Keep in mind this is also not the first incident.  About 6 months ago he drove drunk (with a suspended license) to a title loan place with his daughter.  The title loan place was so concerned that they called the police.  The police, made someone else come pick him and the girl up and would not allow him to drive home because of the suspended license, but did not drug / alcohol test him.  We did learn later the cop does know the father's lawyer, I don't know if this played a role, but likely.<br />
<br />
One time the daughter came home from visitation with severe bruising in her pelvic area.  She was taken to the hospital where the doctor said it was very extensive and serious and more than a child falling down, not likely sexual but she would have screamed out in pain.  But the court dismissed the doctor and pictures because the father said 'it must have happened at daycare, I didn't notice anything'.  The daycare worker (a woman who runs it out of her house and doesn't want to cause waves, but also apparently doesn't care about the interest of the child) said it was possible, but she doesn't remember anything either.  To answer the obvious question, we've tried to convince the mother to switch to a different, better daycare that would report abuse but she doesn't have enough money.  And unfortunately makes too much money to get help from the state, even though she only makes like 30k a year I think.<br />
<br />
He's also on video of making skype calls with his daughter to the mother in an obviously high state.  The video's aren't great, but you can see where he slurs speech and has trouble even staying awake on camera while holding the child.<br />
<br />
Here's the bottom line:<br />
<ul><li style="">He uses heroin regularly, while in custody of his daughter.</li><li style="">One mutual friend of the mother even let slip he did heroin with the father as recent as a month ago.  I'm pretty sure he's doing it every week, he can't stop himself.</li><li style="">The child has repeatedly said daddy passes out and sleeps a lot when she's there.</li><li style="">The child's blanket has 6 burn marks on it from when he was passed out.  She says 'she had to wake up daddy to put out the fire', they look like cigarette burns to me.</li><li style="">Even after a year and a half the mother is responsible for his health care because they are still married.</li><li style="">Because they are still married there is no child support yet (I think).  He may have been ordered to pay some, but he doesn't work and has never paid any.</li><li style="">Her lawyer is terrible, but because she's already paid him 6k she's broke and doesn't have enough to retain a new one.  Honestly I'm not sure how his overly poor performance is not criminal.  Besides showing up for court he's done no obvious work and my wife seems to know more about custody court than he does.</li><li style="">CPS is aware of all of this and has refused to do anything, claiming the child is fine.  The one time they issued a protection order it was rescinded and the one time they said they would drug test, they never did.</li><li style="">He has now convinced the child to say not only bad things about mommy's new daddy, but that he touches her in inappropriate places. I know the guy, he's great, and these claims didn't start until the girl said she like's mommy's boyfriend better than daddy.  He's also rarely alone with the girl.</li><li style="">He also regularly doesn't even show for his scheduled visitations.  Which i realize is minor compared to everything else, but it really messes with their lives too.  Which honestly I thought was enough to get you in trouble if you do it often enough.  But apparently not.</li></ul><br />
<br />
I'm at my wits end because this child is going to die.  If not now, eventually.  Either he does something stupid with her in the car / house or she learns his drug ways and is her own addict at an early age.  He's already driven drunk / high with her in the car and nearly burned the house down while passed out.<br />
<br />
This is something I can't watch happen.  But what am I supposed to do when CPS, the police and the court system all refuse to do anything about it?  I know people blow things out of proportion when custody is at stake, but there is simply too much here to ignore, stuff that I know is true and has more witnesses than just an angry mother.  But that's basically how they treat her, as an angry ex wife who will say anything to deny him custody.  But all it really looks like is they are all getting paid off by his lawyer to give him the child.<br />
<br />
If anyone has any ideas I'm all ears.  Something has to be done to save the child.  I've tried to find ways to get her money back from the lawyer (so she has money to get a new one), but that seems impossible unless he's actually missed court dates.  We've had dozens of people calling CPS, and not just 'mommy's friends'.  And worst of all, google has failed to help me find another solution.  Damn you google!</div>

]]></content:encoded>
