			<title>Personal Data Collection in the Workplace</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78128-Personal-Data-Collection-in-the-Workplace&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 14 Sep 2015 20:38:24 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[Summary version of article: employers are experimenting with data chips embedded in the ID lanyards their employees wear. These chips monitor things like how many times an employee pushes away from their desk, how often and for how long they speak at meetings, etc. They're also scanning employee...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Summary version of article: employers are experimenting with data chips embedded in the ID lanyards their employees wear. These chips monitor things like how many times an employee pushes away from their desk, how often and for how long they speak at meetings, etc. They're also scanning employee e-mails to figure out who employees are associating with and for how long.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/how-new-data-collection-technology-might-change-office-culture-1.3196065" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/ho...ture-1.3196065</a><br />
<br />
An organizational behaviour professor thinks that the drawbacks of such data gathering, including discouraging trial-and-error learning, outweigh any perceived benefits:<br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/too-orwellian-companies-monitoring-personal-time-for-self-improvement-1.3196321" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.cbc.ca/news/technology/to...ment-1.3196321</a><br />
<br />
My first instinct, if I worked for a company that tried to implement this, would be to tell the company to get stuffed. While the technology could potentially be used to improve efficiency, I feel it's much more likely to be used improperly: &quot;You only spoke five times last meeting, negative performance review inc.&quot; But would I feel the same way if I were the employer or manager, and it was another source of information I could use to gain insight on employee behaviours? Does anyone here work in an environment where personal behaviour is tracked and monitored, and how do you feel about it?</div>

]]></content:encoded>
